<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12117j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12117j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12117j"> 117(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ far from holding a / modest rank</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Des auteurs classiques et des po&egrave;tes plus r&eacute;cents, sa m&eacute;moire lui conservait des maximes et des vers, qui venaient &agrave; propos &eacute;mailler ses phrases de jolies r&eacute;miniscences. Et lui-m&ecirc;me cultivait, et les vers et la prose. Son style personnel, heurt&eacute;, imag&eacute;, tour &agrave; tour tendre et passionn&eacute;, obs&eacute;quieux ou &eacute;nergique, souvent diffus et redondant, parfois obscur et incorrect, se pla&icirc;t &agrave; l&apos;antith&egrave;se, &agrave; la subtilit&eacute;, aux rapprochements ing&eacute;nieux, aux m&eacute;taphores, aux hyperboles; mais ce sont les d&eacute;fauts de l&apos;&eacute;poque, plus encore que ceux de l&apos;&eacute;crivain, et de l&apos;avis des bons critiques, saint Colomban est loin de tenir un rang modeste dans l&apos;activit&eacute; litt&eacute;raire de la p&eacute;riode m&eacute;rovingienne. <br><font color="green">[He remembered the maxims and verses of Classical authors and more recent poets, that came <mark>to spangle his sentences with relevant and beautiful reminiscences.</mark> He himself practised both verse and prose. His personal style was abrupt, full of imagery, by turns tender and passionate, obsequious or energetic, often diffuse and redundant, sometimes obscure and incorrect. It delighted in antithesis, in nuances, in ingenious combinations, in metaphors, in hyperboles. But these are more the faults of the time than those of the writer and according to the opinion of good critics Saint Columbanus is <mark>far from having a modest rank</mark> in the literary activity of the Merovingian period.]</font> <small> <a name="STCM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#STCM"><cite title="source">Saint Colomban</cite></a> (1905) 178</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
